Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

04:00 PM Defendant Travis D. Westaby via phone from Dunn Co. Jail with Attorney Jonathan Bradley Lundeen via Zoom videoconferencing.  Agent Kyle Severson via Zoom videoconferencing.  DA Sean Edward Froelich appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court advises Defendant of right to present, Defendant understands and waives.  Atty. Lundeen advises that he spoke with Defendant but Mr. Westaby did not receive the entire packet.  Court questions Defendant, he wishes to proceed w/Sentencing.  DA Froelich states there is an agreement as to sentence credit of 62 days.  DA Froelich states position, notes violations, considerations and factors.  Recommending 9-12 months.  Notes $30 paid towards restitution w/remaining balance of $3,160.02.  In lieu of civil judgment, State is recommending Court order Clerk to turn debt over to SDC for collection.  Atty. Lundeen states positions, advises of Dunn Co. case.  Recommending 6 months due to pending Dunn Co. case.  Requests work release, 30 day furlough to obtain EHM and time to pay on restitution.  State responds to EHM, noting costs that could go toward restitution.  Atty. Lundeen responds re: Dunn Co. Jail policy but due to COVID they are not accepting new people on Huber.  Defendant makes statement.  Court advises of considerations.  Court sentences Defendant to six months, 45 days good time/62 days served.  Neither Huber/EHM is granted.  73 days remaining.  Release date of July 8, 2020.  Court orders restitution be turned over the SDC if half is not paid by 12/31 and balance by 04/01.  Court advises of appeal rights.  Adjourned at 4:25 PM
